</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DD29E90F426413C23D005BFD8A965DCE" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2966C9EE83C7AF3463C87760CEDDDF63" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1870104B1D06A03C8DBF263DCBB6CCF6" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The species is placed in 
<taxonomicName id="8011FB04B0A94F4664933CA79FF19F3C" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6F10E8CBA891733EAFCD7FE1855AECDA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it possesses a combination of characters similar to that cited in the introduction.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B6D65873EF7E5EE45A5299C3B59B708B" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
<taxonomicName id="6CF2AD87BB309893FE63C27B1CFBC41A" authorityName="Lai &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus beaveri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beaveri">
<emphasis id="623A3AC92D1C74651DF0BE6CC6C3F1FD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus beaveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3E39234540C700DBD08C22FF60EB3354" authorityName="Lai &amp; Zhang &amp; Li &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Browne" baseAuthorityYear="1975" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus brevis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="6B4492FD11F8D2ECC19CE6B433FF65FE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Browne, 1975) (new combination, see below) and 
<taxonomicName id="035EBBB7E83BE33802ED717025E8EDF9" authorityName="Browne" authorityYear="1955" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus platypoides" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platypoides">
<emphasis id="903CDFE7350274DF27AA2B80D0032856" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus platypoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Browne, 1955). They can be easily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName id="78888280990F67DBE77662468B5ED389" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BC41BCFE7A267D7F77BA6F15547A9D40" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the male elytral apex truncate with a large, circular, concave declivity. The elytral apex of male of 
<taxonomicName id="10E858DA53DE0535323A297E87E5B2D3" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Verbenaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. beaveri" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="beaveri">
<emphasis id="34D259A95115984060D732EF2A7A7B09" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. beaveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and that of 
<taxonomicName id="34AA144E10A2B285BB7597C9A8B1D70B" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Verbenaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. brevis" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="E76F554DA9FDFD48041BA229ED718D25" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess a deep, acutely margined declivity, with a broad, almost circular, apical emargination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
